4.a) fork() is used to create a new child process from the exisiting parent process by duplicating it.
 exec() is used to a new program by replacing the current running process.
4.b) wait() is used to stop the execution of parent process until its child process finishes or stops.
4.c)
START
Create a child process using fork()
IF fork() return 0 THEN
 Execute ls l using exec()
ELSE IF parent process
 Wait for child process to finish 
 show "child process completed"
ELSE
show "fork failed"
END IF
END
#include <stdio.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>
int main()
{
    pid_t pid;
    pid=fork();
    if(pid==0){
        execlp("ls","ls","-1",NULL);
        printf("execution failed\n");
